You’re touching a real idea that shows up in a lot of fields: representing disagreements as coordinates in a space instead of as “right vs wrong.” When you do that, arguments become data structures you can analyze.

1. Turning Arguments into Coordinates

Imagine every argument point as a vector in a space.

A simple version might be:
	•	X — Scale (individual ↔ system / micro ↔ macro)
	•	Y — Time horizon (immediate ↔ long-term)
	•	Z — Value weighting (efficiency ↔ fairness, stability ↔ innovation, etc.)

Each person’s statement becomes a point or direction in that space.

Instead of:

“You’re wrong.”

You get:

“You’re at (micro, short-term, efficiency) and I’m at (macro, long-term, fairness).”

Now disagreement becomes distance between vectors, not hostility.

⸻

2. Braiding the Threads

Your “braided cord” metaphor actually fits well.

If each perspective is a strand:
	•	One strand = economic lens
	•	One strand = ethical lens
	•	One strand = technological lens

When braided together, you get a stronger model of reality than any single strand.

This is how interdisciplinary work operates:
economics + psychology + engineering → better prediction than any one alone.

⸻

3. Noise vs Signal

When you step back far enough, a lot of arguments look like noise because:
	•	people are sampling different scales
	•	they’re using different definitions
	•	they’re optimizing different variables

In signal-processing terms, debate is often multiple signals overlapping in the same channel.

Separating them by coordinate system clarifies what’s actually being said.

⸻

4. The “Static” Insight

Your comment about static has a philosophical parallel.

When you observe a system long enough, you may notice:
	•	many arguments repeat the same structural patterns
	•	the surface content changes, but the underlying axes stay similar

Examples:
	•	security vs freedom
	•	stability vs change
	•	individual vs collective

Different centuries, same axes.

⸻

5. Why Mapping Helps

If you treat discourse like data:

You can:
	•	cluster similar viewpoints
	•	detect hidden assumptions
	•	identify missing dimensions

Instead of winning an argument, you improve the map.

⸻

A funny thing happens when people get good at this:
arguments stop feeling like battles and start feeling like coordinate transformations.

You’re not defeating someone — you’re figuring out what basis they’re working in.